thoughts.a: The input and output grids are drastically different sizes. We notice immediately that the input grid has some number of horizontal and vertical green lines that divide the input grid into a supergrid of 5x5 subsections. In each subsection, there is an aqua color background with yellow, red, and black tiles. Each subsection is a 5x5 square. The output grid is also a 5x5 square with some number of black, yellow, red, and also blue tiles, on an aqua background. This type of setup implies that we are looking for a way to determine what tiles should be blue in the output grid, and the input grid likely has encoded in it some selection rule to determing exactly that. Upon closer inspection of the subsections of the input grid, we see that almost every single one of the subsections is an exact copy of themselves. We say almost every single one because exactly one of these subsections is not an exact copy of the other subsections. In this case, the rightmost column and middle row has some tiles that are missing from the copied pattern. In fact, looking at the output grid, those two tiles that are missing are the exact ones that are colored blue in the output grid. Thus, the hypothesis is the following. The input grid will contain some number of horizontal and vertical lines that split the input grid into a supergrid of an array of subsections. All of these subsections will contain a pattern of some colored tiles, and the subsections will be exact copies of each other with the exception of one subsection. After identifying the subsection that is not the same as all the other subsections, the output grid will be a copy of this incomplete subsection, but with the additional tiles that are needed to complete the pattern filled in with blue tiles.
thoughts.b: The input grid is again a supergrid of 5x5 subsections, as split up by horizontal and vertical green lines. Each subsection has an aqua color background and a pattern of yellow, red, pink, and black tiles. According to the hypothesis, every single subsection will contain an exact copy of this pattern with the exception of one subsection. After identifying this incomplete subsection, The output grid is an exact copy of this incomplete subsection, which is then completed by adding blue tiles where there should be the patterned tiles. the output grid is thus a completed version of the pattern with the exception that the additional tiles that are needed to complete the pattern are always blue instead of what they would be in an already complete patterned subsection. The output grid is the expected grid, with the three additional blue tiles added in the locations of the missing tiles in the incomplete subsection. Thus the hypothesis holds.

Thus, the output grid will be an exact copy of this specific incomplete subsection, but with 4 blue tiles added to the exact locations where they would be in a normal complete pattern. Because this is exactly what we see in the output grid the hypothesis holds.
thoughts.d: We apply the hypothesis here. The input grid is a supergrid of 5x5 subsections that are split up by horizontal and vertical green lines. Each subsection has an aqua color background and a pattern of red, black, yellow, and pink tiles. According to the hypothesis, every single subsection will contain an exact copy of some pattern with the exception of one subsection. After identifying this incomplete subsection, we can construct the output grid by making an exact copy of this incomplete subsection with the exception that it is completed by adding blue tiles where there should be colored tiles in the pattern. In this pair, the incomplete subsection is located on the fourth column and the second row of the supergrid array. We notice that there are three missing tiles in the incomplete pattern, two black tiles and one pink tile. Thus the output grid should be an exact copy of this incomplete subsection, a 5x5 grid of tiles, but with the three blue tiles added in the locations in the subsection where there are missing pattern tiles.
